to remove all the containers in once 
====>docker container rm -f $(docker container ls -aq)
to remove all the images in once
===> docker image rm -f $(docker image ls -aq)

docker build -t <dir> <name of the image> // to build image
docker run -it <name of the image> // to run the container

docker run -it -p 8080:8080 <name of the image> // to run the container with port

docker-compose up // to run the container multiple container at once


docker-compose build // to build the container
docker-compose build --no-cache  // to build the container without cache
docker-compose up -d // to run the container in background

docker-compose down // to stop the container and remove it from the system



/// 
DNS, or Domain Name System, is a hierarchical and distributed naming system that translates human-readable domain names 
(like "google.com" or "wikipedia.org") into machine-readable IP addresses (like "142.250.184.196" or "208.80.154.224"). 
It acts like a giant phonebook for the internet, mapping easily remembered names to the numerical addresses needed to locate 
and connect to specific online resources.